tr.td: Title: Office Visit Note
Author: Lalla MD, Michael J

1. Hemorrhoids K64.9
Patient's initial complaint and presentation was for hemorrhoidal disease. Patient has had hemorrhoidal disease for about 10 years. Patient does not take any fiber supplements. I have advised the patient to start taking fiber supplements. This will help bulk up her stool and make her incidence of symptomatic hemorrhoidal disease decrease. Patient also understands it may take 2 to 3 months before the fiber starts having any significant effect.
2. History of colon polyps Z86.010
The patient also has a history of colon polyps on her last colonoscopy was about 6 years ago. I have recommended a high risk screening colonoscopy to the patient. I have explained the procedure and its risks in great detail and provided the patient with written literature on the same. The risks of the procedure include but are not limited to post procedure bleeding infection and perforation. This could necessitate exploration through a laparotomy or thoracotomy with repair resection or diversion of any injured area in the form of an ostomy. There is a chance of false negative exam meaning that there possibly would be a lesion that would not be visualized at the time of endoscopy. This could delay the discovery of this lesion and possibly have negative consequences for the patient. There is a chance of incomplete visualization of the colon. This could necessitate completion radiologic studies. The patient understands this and wishes to proceed.

Chief Complaint
Hemorrhoids
History of Present Illness
Patient is a 68-year-old female presenting for consultation for hemorrhoids. Patient has had banding of her hemorrhoids before which did not help. I did ask the patient if she takes any fiber supplements. She does not. We then discussed the relationship between fiber intake and hemorrhoid disease. Patient also noted that she is overdue for a colonoscopy. Her last colonoscopy was about 6 years ago and she had several polyps removed. She would like to have a colonoscopy performed. She denies any family history of colon cancer. She denies any significant amount of blood in her stool. She denies any significant weight loss.
Review of Systems

Neurologic: Alert & oriented X 4

Physical Exam
Vitals & Measurements
T: 37.2 °C (Oral) HR: 113(Peripheral) RR: 18 BP: 147/94 SpO2: 98%
HT: 162.56 cm WT: 78.11 kg BMI: 30
HEENT the patient's extraocular muscles are intact. The patient's cranial nerves are intact. Patient has intact hearing to light sound on both sides. Eyes the patient's pupils are equally round and reactive to light. Extraocular muscles are intact. Neck is supple with no masses or bruits. There is no adenopathy. There is no JVD. Thyroid is palpably normal with no masses. Thyroid rises and falls normally on swallowing. Chest reveals good breath sounds bilaterally. No rales or rhonchi. Symmetric rise and fall of chest bilaterally. Heart is of regular rate and rhythm. There are no gallops rubs or murmurs. There is no palpable cardiac thrill. There is a normal radial and carotid pulse. Abdomen is soft nontender and nondistended. There is no organomegaly on exam. There are no hernias on exam. There are normal bowel sounds. Extremities are warm normal palpable pulses.
Assessment/Plan
1. Hemorrhoids K64.9
Patient's initial complaint and presentation was for hemorrhoidal disease. Patient has had hemorrhoidal disease for about 10 years. Patient does not take any fiber supplements. I have advised the patient to start taking fiber supplements. This will help bulk up her stool and make her incidence of symptomatic hemorrhoidal disease decrease. Patient also understands it may take 2 to 3 months before the fiber starts having any significant effect.
2. History of colon polyps Z86.010
The patient also has a history of colon polyps on her last colonoscopy was about 6 years ago. I have recommended a high risk screening colonoscopy to the patient. I have explained the procedure and its risks in great detail and provided the patient with written literature on the same. The risks of the procedure include but are not limited to post procedure bleeding infection and perforation. This could necessitate exploration through a laparotomy or thoracotomy with repair resection or diversion of any injured area in the form of an ostomy. There is a chance of false negative exam meaning that there possibly would be a lesion that would not be visualized at the time of endoscopy. This could delay the discovery of this lesion and possibly have negative consequences for the patient. There is a chance of incomplete visualization of the colon. This could necessitate completion radiologic studies. The patient understands this and wishes to proceed.
